article.description: Raymar Morgan and Durrell Summers both scored 16 points and Drew Neitzel added 14 to help Michigan State beat San Jose State 85-45 in a matchup of Spartans on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Morgan, Summers help Michigan State conquer San Jose State
article.linkText: Michigan St. victorious in battle of Spartans
article.story: EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Tom Izzo saw enough errors in Michigan State's 40-point victory over San Jose State to make him glad it was Wednesday night and not Saturday. An 85-45 dismantling of another team called the Spartans didn't inspire much confidence in Izzo that his team could handle Texas (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) this weekend at The Palace of Auburn Hills. "If we don't practice a lot different and don't play a lot different than we played tonight, we won't win the next one," Izzo insisted. "That's not motivation. That's a fact." The numbers Wednesday night suggested that Michigan State (10-1) can play with any team in the nation. Michigan State (No. 10 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) had 26 assists to four for San Jose State (3-5). Michigan State also had 16 steals, blocked 13 shots -- the most in Izzo's 13 seasons -- and ran well enough to score 25 points off 23 turnovers. Freshman Durrell Summers answered a halftime critique and finished with a career-high 16 points, coming off the bench to delight the crowd with acrobatic plays. "Coach let me know that I wasn't playing very well," Summers said. "I knew I was terrible. But I came out and tried to forget the first half." Michigan State scored the first 12 points of the game and led 36-31 at halftime. But a 25-21 rebounding deficit was all the ammunition Izzo needed. "Things like that will get us absolutely killed on Saturday," Izzo said. "I didn't think this was a 40-point game. And we have a ton of work to do to get ready to play a team like Texas." Raymar Morgan scored 16 points on 6-for-10 shooting from the field for Michigan State, while Drew Neitzel added 14 points and seven assists and was 6-for-9 from the field. Goran Suton dominated the first few minutes at both ends and finished with 11 points, seven rebounds, four blocked shots and four steals. "We could get any shot we wanted tonight," Suton said. "I can't tell you if we would've won or not if we'd been playing Texas, but it would've been a lot closer." Freshman Kalin Lucas had 10 points, while Travis Walton played a superior floor game with 10 assists, one turnover and four steals. "Going into a game like the one we'll play Saturday, you want to be building on every aspect," Walton said. "Coach didn't think we were doing that, even though we won by 40." Michigan State shot 56.4 percent in the second half and 52.8 for the game. San Jose State shot 30 percent, just 24.2 percent in the first half, and was 1-for-11 from 3-point range for the game. DeShawn Wright led San Jose State with 17 points, and Chris Oakes had nine in his first game after transferring from Pepperdine. "Michigan State was clearly a lot better," San Jose State coach George Nessman said. "We lost our composure in the second half. No question, defensively, I thought they played really well. Whenever you commit more than 20 turnovers, you have to credit the other team." That was more credit than Michigan State was willing to give itself as it prepares to meet the Longhorns and guards D.J. Augustin and A.J. Abrams. "It's a big challenge for everyone here," Walton said. "It's an honor to be able to guard the best point guard in the nation. But if you're any kind of player, that's why you come to Michigan State."
